608 Oakland Avenue - a magnificent 1919 Craftsman style home in  lively Old West Austin, w. walking proximity to dining, retail, recreation. Quirky, quaint and charming, the house is full of the soul of a bygone era.  The elegant simplicity of the style lends itself to modern renovation.

608 Oakland Avenue - a magnificent 1919 Craftsman style home in  lively Old West Austin, w. walking proximity to dining, retail, recreation. Quirky, quaint and charming, the house is full of the soul of a bygone era.  The elegant simplicity of the style lends itself to modern renovation.
A light-filled sunroom to the left. Above is the large atelier/bedroom, from which there is a spectacular view of the city skyline.  The roof is metal.

608 Oakland Ave in the heart of Old West Austin - colorful urban living in a 1919 Craftsman style home. The house sits high above the avenue, with a flight of stairs in front.  Street level entry to back porch and kitchen are on 6 1/2 St.
Welcome to 608 Oakland Ave in Old West Austin/Clarksville - a colorful example of the Craftsman style.
The front porch, high above the street, invites relaxation and socializing.

View from the front porch facing east/southeast - the big skies of Texas, the skyline of downtown Austin.  From the second floor you can see from the Capitol to the Zilker Park Christmas tree and Ferris wheel.

The Austin skyline from the second floor.  The windows in this room face west and south - the nighttime view is spectacular.  You can see the Zilker Christmas tree and ferris wheel during the holidays.
The cozy hearth in the 1919 Craftsman  living room is reflected in the original wood flooring.   The painted shiplap walls recall a bygone era of sold craftsmanship.
The large living room looking east  toward the front porch -taken from the dining room -airy and full of light.  Painted shiplap walls.
Typical Craftsman pillars with bookcases (now enclosed) divide the living room and the dining room - there is great flow and high ceilings on the first level.
Five panel doors with typical molding, painted shiplap walls, and beautiful original wood flooring are details of the era.  This door leads to a roomy bedroom off the living room.
The roomy front bedroom off the living room, now used as the owner's office - full of light.
A view from the living room to the front porch that extends along the front of the home.  A classic period door.  Rooms are airy and full of light.
A view of the living room and the front door from the dining room.
The warm dining room is large, with a window seat.  The blue wall is painted wallpaper over the shiplap, as they did it in the old days - no sheetrock here.
Looking out from the dining room, where there is a cozy window seat with underseat storage.
The spacious library/billiards room can be closed off by French doors.  In the rear left is the sun room, to the right, stairs lead to the upper floor.

Passing from the dining room to the large farmhouse kitchen with colorfully painted wood floors.  French doors to the left lead to a large room of versatility utility - library, billiards room, music room.  Note white painted shiplap walls and ceiling of solid wood throughout that showcases the house's artisanal solidity and the craftsmanship of a bygone era.

The large colorful kitchen with a center island and pantry is the realm of a professional chef.  There is plenty of room in the pantry or adjoining hall closet to renovate and install a washer and dryer.  Many possibilities.
A rustic farmhouse sink of vintage charm.
Farmhouse kitchen has beamed ceiling, plentiful light.
A true cook's kitchen  - vintage style.
Colorful stairs leading to the second floor where there are two spacious bedrooms and a full bathroom as well as attic storage spaces.
The stairway from the upper floor is painted in cheerful colors.
The colorful stairwell is accented by an old colored glass panel that looks into the sunroom.
Period doorknob on a painted door.
A bedroom or artist's atelier on the second floor - full of light and with spectacular views east to downtown and south to Zilker. Spectacular city skyline view at night.
A cozy corner of the living room.
A whimsical repurposing of the old telephone niche in the hallway, with vintage inspired wall-paper.  Note the Craftsman five panel door and vintage doorknob.
Style in the main floor bathroom.  Another full bath and two bedrooms are upstairs.
Solid old wood doors throughout the home, with painted wooden shiplap walls and ceilings reflect the quality of the Craftsman era.
A view of the sunroom windows on the first floor which face south and east, with a large bedroom above.   Basement below.
A corner of the master bedroom.  Painted shiplap walls reveal the old style craftsmanship as does the millwork around the doors.
A stained glass window in the sun room looking up the stairs to the upper floor.
The  side yard in winter.  There is a curb cut from the street and there used to be a garage in the back long ago.  Note the deck to the right which overlooks the yard toward the south and east.
A wintry view from the porch over the rooftops.  This is a neighborhood of many Craftsman bungalows.  Even on overcast days there is plenty of light throughout the house from all the windows.
Space heaters warm the house.
The spacious bathroom on the first floor - the window looks onto the back deck.
A vintage wall space heater keeps the downstairs bathroom warm and cozy on chilly winter mornings.
